definition.value: Compounds containing two phosphane groups linked directly by a P-P bond or via a hydrocarbon bridge.
An organosulfur heterocyclic compound containing a six-member aliphatic saturated heterocycle made up of two sulfur atoms and four carbon atoms.
A group derived from triazole by removal of a hydrogen atom.
A tetramethylrhodamine compound having a carboxy substituent at the 5-position
Compounds containing a mono-unsaturated furan ring skeleton.
A member of the class of anthracenes that is anthracene in which both of the hydrogens on the central ring are substituted by phenyl groups.
A dihydrofuran that is 2,3-dihydrofuran substituted by a methyl group at position 4.
Any methoxybenzene that consists of a benzene skeleton substituted with two methoxy groups and its derivatives.
Any aromatic ether that consists of a benzene skeleton substituted with one or more methoxy groups.
Boranes containing only two B atoms, linked either directly by a B-B bond or via hydrogen bridging atoms.

An organic heterotetracyclic compound 7,11b-dihydroindeno[2,1-c]chromene carrying five hydroxy substituents at positions 3, 4, 6a, 9 and 10. The most important and most used dye in histology, histochemistry, histopathology and in cytology.
An ortho-fused polycyclic arene found commonly in the coal tar.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated aldehyde of general formula R(1)R(2)C=CR(3)-CH=O in which the aldehydic C=O function is conjugated to a C=C double bond at the alpha,beta position.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated ketone of general formula R(1)R(2)C=CR(3)-C(=O)R(4) (R(4) =/= H) in which the C=O function is conjugated to a C=C double bond at the alpha,beta position.
A hydroxycoumarin that is 6-methoxycoumarin in which the hydrogens at positions 7 and 8 have been replaced by hydroxy groups.
A compound containing a conjugated system of an amine, an alkene and a ketone.
